article.headline: Stanford 73, San Jose State 52
article.story: STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Stanford coach Trent Johnson knows his young players will have both their good and bad moments. He's just hoping the good ones last longer. Lawrence Hill scored nine of his 17 points within seven minutes of the second half, helping Stanford beat San Jose State 73-52 in the first round of the CBE Classic on Tuesday night. "We were good in spurts and we were ugly at times," Johnson said. "We had foul trouble with the young guys. It's a learning experience. We kept our composure and guys made a couple of plays." Robin Lopez added half of his 12 points in a four-minute span as the Cardinal (2-0) advances into the second round against Air Force, a 69-68 winner over Long Beach State in an earlier game. That winner earns a trip to the Classic's Final Four in Kansas City next Monday. Anthony Goods added 11 points, three days after blistering Siena for 30. "A few times we went to a fast break and that's something coach Johnson wants us to do more often," Hill said. "Sometimes, though, we went too fast and either turned it over or weren't in position to get a rebound." Harry Brown and Jamon Hill each scored 12 points to lead San Jose State (0-2), which lost its ninth straight to a Pac-10 school. "Stanford just wore us down with their physicalness and their size," San Jose State coach George Nessman said. "We couldn't finish our shots -- and in a game against a good Pac-10 team like Stanford, you have to finish your shots." Relying on a bevy of sophomores and freshmen, the Cardinal managed to work their way through inconsistent play to get the win. Stanford coach Trent Johnson has one healthy junior and two seniors at his disposal. Both senior Fred Washington and junior Taj Finger were in foul trouble through the second half. Lopez, the highly regarded seven-footer who recorded a double-double in his first collegiate game against Siena on Saturday, also spent much of the contest riding the bench due to foul trouble. When Lopez was on the court, Stanford made sure he got the ball inside to him. With 9:55 left, he finished a lob pass from Mitch Johnson with a hard dunk. "You can't argue with 4-for-5 from the field and 4-for-5 from the free throw line," Johnson said. "He only played 16 minutes. He's not going to be great all the time. What I like about him is that he adjusts to the circumstances. When he first came out he was frustrated at himself. But he made the adjustments." The Spartans, who won six games last year, managed to stay within reach of Stanford through the first half. Buoyed by a pair of transfers -- Tim Pierce from Arizona State and Kerry Woolridge from Minnesota -- San Jose State rallied from an early 13-point deficit and were within six of the Cardinal early in the second half. Stanford took control of the game with a 12-1 run and was ahead 46-29 with 13:38 to play. "We had a difficult time running our offense in general," Nessman said. "You can credit Stanford's defense for much of that problem." The Cardinal held San Jose State to under 30 percent shooting, including 22 percent (6-of-27) in the second half. The Spartans shot 40 percent in their loss to UC Santa Barbara last Friday. Stanford led at halftime 32-25. This was the 50th meeting of the neighboring schools, but the first in 12 years. Stanford leads the series 38-12.
